<DOC><DOCNO> AP900918-0176 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-09-18-90 2305EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-CultTrial     09-18 0265</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Cult Trial,0301</SECOND><HEAD>Cult Leader's Son Convicted of Four Killings</HEAD><BYLINE>By SONJA BARISIC</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>PAINESVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The teen-age son of a religious cultleader was convicted Tuesday of helping his father kill a man andhis three children. Jurors acquitted him of the slaying of thechildren's mother.   Damon Lundgren, 19, listened to the verdicts with his headbowed. He could be sentenced to death.   The jury deliberated for about 11 hours over two days beforeconvicting Lundgren on four murder counts and four counts ofkidnapping in the deaths of Dennis Avery and his three children.   He was acquitted of murder and kidnapping counts in the death ofAvery's wife, Cheryl.   Prosecutor Joseph Gurley said he was satisfied with theverdict.Lundgren's attorney, Albert Purola, declined comment. Thetrial's penalty phase was scheduled to begin Monday.   The convictions came the same day Lundgren's father, JeffreyLundgren, 40, appeared at a sentencing hearing. He was convictedlast month on five murder and kidnapping counts.   The same jury that convicted the elder Lundgren must decidewhether to recommend the death penalty. Other sentencing optionsincluded life in prison without parole for 20 years, and lifewithout parole for 30 years.   Damon Lundgren's mother, Alice, last month received fiveconsecutive life sentences for her conspiracy, complicity andkidnapping convictions.   The Averys were killed April 17, 1989. Each was been bound andgagged, shot to death and dumped into a common grave under a barnat a farm in Kirtland, 30 miles east of Cleveland.   The elder Lundgren is a former lay minister of the ReorganizedChurch of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints, in Kirtland. He wasdefrocked in 1988 for inappropriate conduct and later formed hisown sect.</TEXT></DOC>